{0 day11-layer}

Generic layered storage on disk. A layer is a directory containing a
[fs/] tree (the filesystem delta) plus metadata files.

The core type {!Day11_layer.Layer} represents a layer on disk via its
content hash and directory path, with helpers to check existence and
status. {!Day11_layer.Meta} serializes per-layer metadata ([layer.json])
covering exit status, parent hashes, timing, and disk usage.
{!Day11_layer.Dir} owns the naming convention that derives directory
names from content hashes. {!Day11_layer.Base} represents the
foundational rootfs image at the bottom of every overlay stack.
{!Day11_layer.Hash} computes content-addressed cache keys from layer inputs.
{!Day11_layer.Stack} merges multiple layers into one directory via hardlinked
copies, and plans overlayfs lowerdir layouts that fit kernel page-size
limits. {!Day11_layer.Scan} enumerates layers from the on-disk cache.
{!Day11_layer.Import} extracts layer filesystems from Docker images.
{!Day11_layer.Last_used} maintains a cheap mtime-based sentinel for LRU
eviction. {!Day11_layer.Symlinks} maintains per-identifier tracking
symlinks for layer discovery.

Depends on {!day11-sys} for subprocess and sudo access. Has no opam
or package-domain knowledge — domain-specific metadata lives in
sidecar files owned by higher libraries.

